1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,081
Why Joan Failed in Retailing Joan is an intelligent, well-educated, attractive girl of 24.

2
00:00:08,270 --> 00:00:16,641
Fresh from college, Joan got a job as an assistant buyer in ready-to-wear goods at a low-to-medium-priced department store.

3
00:00:16,911 --> 00:00:18,721
She came highly recommended.

4
00:00:18,911 --> 00:00:23,200
Joan has ambition, talent, and enthusiasm, one letter read.

5
00:00:23,310 --> 00:00:26,241
She is certain to succeed in a big way.

6
00:00:26,671 --> 00:00:29,440
But Joan did not succeed in a big way.

7
00:00:29,630 --> 00:00:34,241
Joan lasted only eight months, and then quit retailing for other work.

8
00:00:35,231 --> 00:00:39,440
I knew her buyer well, and one day I asked him what happened.

9
00:00:40,031 --> 00:00:44,481
Joan is a fine girl, and she has many fine qualities, he said.

10
00:00:44,591 --> 00:00:46,961
But she had one major limitation.

11
00:00:47,150 --> 00:00:48,880
What was that, I asked.

12
00:00:49,231 --> 00:00:55,440
Well, Joan was forever buying merchandise that she liked, but most of our customers didn't.

13
00:00:55,870 --> 00:01:04,081
She selected styles, colors, materials, and prices she liked without putting herself in the shoes of the people who shop here.

14
00:01:04,430 --> 00:01:08,721
When I'd suggest to her that maybe a certain line wasn't right for us,

15
00:01:08,750 --> 00:01:10,961
she'd say, oh, they'll love this.

16
00:01:11,070 --> 00:01:11,841
I do.

17
00:01:12,031 --> 00:01:13,921
I think this will move fast.

18
00:01:14,671 --> 00:01:17,440
Joan had been brought up in a well-to-do home.

19
00:01:17,710 --> 00:01:20,320
She had been educated to want quality.

20
00:01:20,430 --> 00:01:22,481
Price was not important to her.

21
00:01:22,830 --> 00:01:27,680
Joan just couldn't see clothing through the eyes of low- to middle-income people.

22
00:01:27,791 --> 00:01:31,361
So, the merchandise she bought just wasn't suitable.

23
00:01:32,190 --> 00:01:33,440
The point is this.

24
00:01:33,710 --> 00:01:38,880
To get others to do what you want them to do, you must see things through their eyes.

25
00:01:39,150 --> 00:01:44,961
When you trade minds, the secret of how to influence other people effectively shows up.

26
00:01:45,471 --> 00:01:55,361
A very successful salesman friend told me he spends a lot of time anticipating how prospects will react to his presentation before he gives it.

27
00:01:55,870 --> 00:02:02,000
Trading minds with the audience helps the speaker design a more interesting, harder-hitting talk.

28
00:02:02,430 --> 00:02:09,281
Trading minds with employees helps the supervisor provide more effective, better-received instructions.

29
00:02:10,351 --> 00:02:15,281
A young credit executive explained to me how this technique worked for him.

30
00:02:15,870 --> 00:02:22,081
When I was brought into this store, a medium-sized clothing store, as assistant credit manager,

31
00:02:22,270 --> 00:02:24,241
I was assigned the job of handling all collection correspondence.
